WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.800 align:middle line:90%


00:00:00.800 --> 00:00:03.180 align:middle line:84%
>> This was one of my favorite
interviews of the year.

00:00:03.180 --> 00:00:05.340 align:middle line:84%
Many of us know that
something is terribly

00:00:05.340 --> 00:00:07.410 align:middle line:84%
wrong with the unnatural
way in which we're

00:00:07.410 --> 00:00:08.580 align:middle line:90%
living on the Earth.

00:00:08.580 --> 00:00:11.100 align:middle line:84%
We've created an artificial
environment for life

00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:13.320 align:middle line:84%
in virtually every
way, including--

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:15.600 align:middle line:84%
and especially--
our food supplies.

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:18.270 align:middle line:84%
The deepening crisis
of manufactured food

00:00:18.270 --> 00:00:20.400 align:middle line:84%
and its effect on the
human body and mind

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:22.150 align:middle line:90%
is evidenced everywhere.

00:00:22.150 --> 00:00:25.340 align:middle line:84%
Leonid Sharashkin is a
lifelong gardener from Russia

00:00:25.340 --> 00:00:28.020 align:middle line:84%
that is also the publisher
of the English edition

00:00:28.020 --> 00:00:30.270 align:middle line:84%
of "The Ringing
Cedars" series of books

00:00:30.270 --> 00:00:33.720 align:middle line:84%
about the wisdom of a Siberian
woman named Anastasia.

00:00:33.720 --> 00:00:36.210 align:middle line:84%
The stories are profound
and have left everybody

00:00:36.210 --> 00:00:38.090 align:middle line:90%
wondering who Anastasia is.

00:00:38.090 --> 00:00:47.860 align:middle line:90%


00:00:47.860 --> 00:00:52.450 align:middle line:84%
I first became aware of the
work that you represent--

00:00:52.450 --> 00:00:54.550 align:middle line:84%
and I have to clarify
that a little later on.

00:00:54.550 --> 00:00:57.730 align:middle line:10%
You represent a lot of things,
but "The Ringing Cedars" series

00:00:57.730 --> 00:00:59.475 align:middle line:10%
from a girlfriend
that said, have

00:00:59.475 --> 00:01:01.360 align:middle line:10%
you read "The Ringing
Cedars" series

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:05.200 align:middle line:10%
yet and heard about the words,
the wisdom of Anastasia?

00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:06.946 align:middle line:90%
And I had to admit I hadn't.

00:01:06.946 --> 00:01:08.320 align:middle line:84%
So when I came to
the conference,

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:10.660 align:middle line:84%
I was thrilled to
see that you were

00:01:10.660 --> 00:01:14.650 align:middle line:84%
here and that series of books
and got an immediate rush when

00:01:14.650 --> 00:01:16.630 align:middle line:90%
I saw the cover of the books.

00:01:16.630 --> 00:01:20.720 align:middle line:84%
They're very childlike
and playful and whimsical.

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:24.640 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about what
the Anastasia series,

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:26.440 align:middle line:84%
"The Ringing Cedar"
series of books

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:30.070 align:middle line:84%
is all about, because
this is just fascinating.

00:01:30.070 --> 00:01:34.330 align:middle line:84%
>> It would be very hard to say
what it is about because it is

00:01:34.330 --> 00:01:36.250 align:middle line:90%
basically about everything.

00:01:36.250 --> 00:01:39.280 align:middle line:84%
But it tells the story of a
Russian entrepreneur named

00:01:39.280 --> 00:01:42.960 align:middle line:84%
Vladimir Megre who,
in 1994 and 1995,

00:01:42.960 --> 00:01:46.550 align:middle line:84%
was undertaking trading
expeditions in Siberia

00:01:46.550 --> 00:01:48.940 align:middle line:84%
and was going to
very remote places,

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:50.910 align:middle line:90%
trading with local people.

00:01:50.910 --> 00:01:54.910 align:middle line:84%
And on one of the streets, he
heard fascinating local legends

00:01:54.910 --> 00:01:57.370 align:middle line:84%
about ringing cedar
trees, the trees

00:01:57.370 --> 00:02:02.450 align:middle line:84%
that accumulate so much energy
that they start vibrating.

00:02:02.450 --> 00:02:07.180 align:middle line:84%
And a piece of this cedar
wood worn on one's body

00:02:07.180 --> 00:02:12.940 align:middle line:84%
could improve health and
even make a person happier.

00:02:12.940 --> 00:02:19.570 align:middle line:84%
He disregarded these legends
and dismissed them as fantasy.

00:02:19.570 --> 00:02:21.400 align:middle line:84%
But when he came
back from that trip,

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:24.680 align:middle line:84%
he started researching on the
properties of the Siberian

00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:27.700 align:middle line:84%
cedar and realized
that these trees got

00:02:27.700 --> 00:02:32.510 align:middle line:84%
huge commercial potential, that
produce the Siberian pine nuts

00:02:32.510 --> 00:02:35.830 align:middle line:84%
and the everything of this
tree-- the root, the needles,

00:02:35.830 --> 00:02:38.170 align:middle line:84%
the bark have great
medicinal properties

00:02:38.170 --> 00:02:41.330 align:middle line:84%
that are known in this area
for thousands of years,

00:02:41.330 --> 00:02:44.350 align:middle line:84%
even before Europeans
and Russians arrived.

00:02:44.350 --> 00:02:47.470 align:middle line:84%
So being a keen
entrepreneur that he is,

00:02:47.470 --> 00:02:49.660 align:middle line:84%
he decided to set up
another expedition

00:02:49.660 --> 00:02:52.930 align:middle line:84%
and go back to this area and
to find this ringing cedar

00:02:52.930 --> 00:02:57.150 align:middle line:84%
tree to see how he could cash
in on commercializing it.

00:02:57.150 --> 00:02:59.580 align:middle line:84%
>> So it was totally about
money for him at this point?

00:02:59.580 --> 00:03:03.865 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I have an impression
that it's still the same case.

00:03:03.865 --> 00:03:05.830 align:middle line:84%
>> But let me ask a quick
question right here.

00:03:05.830 --> 00:03:07.210 align:middle line:84%
He says in the
first book that he

00:03:07.210 --> 00:03:08.660 align:middle line:90%
encounters these two old men--

00:03:08.660 --> 00:03:09.560 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:11.230 align:middle line:84%
>> That give him
this information.

00:03:11.230 --> 00:03:13.930 align:middle line:84%
Did that part even happen, that
he encountered two old men?

00:03:13.930 --> 00:03:17.117 align:middle line:84%
Is that who told him about
the lore or how did that go?

00:03:17.117 --> 00:03:17.950 align:middle line:90%
How did he find out?

00:03:17.950 --> 00:03:20.574 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I don't pretend to know
much more than what is written

00:03:20.574 --> 00:03:21.670 align:middle line:90%
in the books.

00:03:21.670 --> 00:03:26.680 align:middle line:84%
Vladimir Megre himself maintains
that this is a real life story

00:03:26.680 --> 00:03:28.630 align:middle line:90%
and a documentary account.

00:03:28.630 --> 00:03:32.950 align:middle line:84%
What we know for sure is that
he was a well-known entrepreneur

00:03:32.950 --> 00:03:36.970 align:middle line:84%
in this part of Siberia, that
during these two years, he did

00:03:36.970 --> 00:03:42.370 align:middle line:84%
take these expeditions up and
down the Siberian river, Ob.

00:03:42.370 --> 00:03:45.200 align:middle line:84%
But whether he, during
this trip, met somebody

00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:48.160 align:middle line:84%
or whether there were
some other kind of source

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:51.040 align:middle line:84%
for this information and
for this inspiration,

00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:53.260 align:middle line:90%
it's up to the reader to judge.

00:03:53.260 --> 00:03:56.220 align:middle line:84%
This is why in the
first book it says--

00:03:56.220 --> 00:03:58.570 align:middle line:84%
the main character,
Anastasia, says--

00:03:58.570 --> 00:04:01.130 align:middle line:84%
I exist for those
for whom I exist,

00:04:01.130 --> 00:04:05.320 align:middle line:84%
and these books are fascinating
in that they can be read either

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:09.020 align:middle line:84%
as a factual documentary
account or a novel,

00:04:09.020 --> 00:04:11.230 align:middle line:90%
but they're neither.

00:04:11.230 --> 00:04:13.570 align:middle line:84%
This question becomes
even irrelevant

00:04:13.570 --> 00:04:16.480 align:middle line:84%
when you consider the
messages that these books are

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:17.500 align:middle line:90%
trying to convey.

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:18.950 align:middle line:90%
>> That's really true.

00:04:18.950 --> 00:04:21.360 align:middle line:84%
First of all, what
does Anastasia mean?

00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:25.100 align:middle line:84%
>> Anastasia in Greek
means Resurrection.

00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:29.040 align:middle line:84%
But actually the root,
anasta, comes from Sanskrit.

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:32.800 align:middle line:84%
And not many people know
that Sanskrit and Russian are

00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:35.560 align:middle line:90%
very closely related languages.

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:38.710 align:middle line:84%
Up to the present day, they
have some common roots.

00:04:38.710 --> 00:04:42.340 align:middle line:84%
And anasta in Sanskrit
means incorruptible,

00:04:42.340 --> 00:04:45.610 align:middle line:84%
something that is so pure
that it cannot be soiled.

00:04:45.610 --> 00:04:47.470 align:middle line:84%
So basically the
word Anastasia is

00:04:47.470 --> 00:04:51.190 align:middle line:90%
a symbol of purity and light.

00:04:51.190 --> 00:04:52.180 align:middle line:90%
>> Very interesting.

00:04:52.180 --> 00:04:54.340 align:middle line:84%
Now the point you make
is quite interesting.

00:04:54.340 --> 00:04:58.330 align:middle line:84%
Whether Vladimir has
actually documented something

00:04:58.330 --> 00:05:00.550 align:middle line:84%
or whether he has come
about this information

00:05:00.550 --> 00:05:05.110 align:middle line:84%
through other extraordinary
means is really not relevant

00:05:05.110 --> 00:05:07.280 align:middle line:84%
when you're reading this
information in one sense,

00:05:07.280 --> 00:05:08.080 align:middle line:90%
is it?

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:11.320 align:middle line:84%
>> What I can tell from
personally knowing the author,

00:05:11.320 --> 00:05:14.440 align:middle line:84%
that he doesn't give an
impression of an individual who

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:17.010 align:middle line:90%
could invent the story.

00:05:17.010 --> 00:05:19.780 align:middle line:84%
He describes himself very
honestly in the books

00:05:19.780 --> 00:05:22.910 align:middle line:84%
and we need to give
him credit for that.

00:05:22.910 --> 00:05:25.210 align:middle line:90%
He smokes.

00:05:25.210 --> 00:05:26.640 align:middle line:90%
He enjoys a drink or--

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:27.440 align:middle line:90%
>> Likes women.

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:29.120 align:middle line:84%
>> He's not indifferent
towards women.

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:31.510 align:middle line:84%
So he is just a
normal entrepreneur

00:05:31.510 --> 00:05:35.530 align:middle line:84%
who enjoys life and tries
to get everything out of it.

00:05:35.530 --> 00:05:36.330 align:middle line:90%
>> Interesting.

00:05:36.330 --> 00:05:38.370 align:middle line:84%
So the second time
he goes back, he's

00:05:38.370 --> 00:05:40.120 align:middle line:84%
going to really squeeze
it for all he can.

00:05:40.120 --> 00:05:41.244 align:middle line:90%
He's going to get the nuts.

00:05:41.244 --> 00:05:43.390 align:middle line:84%
He's going to get
the wood, the oil.

00:05:43.390 --> 00:05:44.770 align:middle line:90%
And then what happens?

00:05:44.770 --> 00:05:47.830 align:middle line:84%
>> According to his account,
he meets the granddaughter

00:05:47.830 --> 00:05:51.500 align:middle line:84%
of the elders to whom he
had talked the year before.

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:53.980 align:middle line:84%
And this woman named
Anastasia wants

00:05:53.980 --> 00:05:56.830 align:middle line:84%
him to spend three days
with her in the depth

00:05:56.830 --> 00:05:59.170 align:middle line:90%
of the wild forest.

00:05:59.170 --> 00:06:00.790 align:middle line:84%
He accepts the
invitation because he

00:06:00.790 --> 00:06:03.460 align:middle line:84%
is keen to see this
ringing cedar tree

00:06:03.460 --> 00:06:07.560 align:middle line:84%
and to see how it could be cut
down, transported to the city,

00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:11.890 align:middle line:84%
and then sawed into
small pieces and sold.

00:06:11.890 --> 00:06:17.290 align:middle line:84%
But his experiences during
these three days with Anastasia

00:06:17.290 --> 00:06:19.330 align:middle line:84%
change his world
view so dramatically,

00:06:19.330 --> 00:06:24.880 align:middle line:84%
because she exhibits knowledge
and feelings and wisdom so

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:27.640 align:middle line:84%
unfamiliar to our
modern civilization

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:32.650 align:middle line:84%
that he, at her request,
drops everything, abandons

00:06:32.650 --> 00:06:35.200 align:middle line:84%
his business,
abandons his family,

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:38.530 align:middle line:84%
and leaves from
Siberia to Moscow

00:06:38.530 --> 00:06:44.290 align:middle line:84%
to write a series of books
about his experiences with her.

00:06:44.290 --> 00:06:47.220 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, all I can say
is, whatever happened,

00:06:47.220 --> 00:06:48.227 align:middle line:90%
I'm glad he did it.

00:06:48.227 --> 00:06:50.560 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about what
happened those first three days

00:06:50.560 --> 00:06:51.580 align:middle line:90%
a little bit--

00:06:51.580 --> 00:06:53.570 align:middle line:84%
from the first book
called "Anastasia," just

00:06:53.570 --> 00:06:55.510 align:middle line:84%
to kind of set the
framework for the types

00:06:55.510 --> 00:06:59.410 align:middle line:84%
of wisdoms that are revealed
in a series of eight books.

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:01.390 align:middle line:84%
Well, now there will
be nine, you say?

00:07:01.390 --> 00:07:03.040 align:middle line:84%
There's another
new one coming out?

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:05.920 align:middle line:84%
>> It's considered the second
part of the book eight,

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:08.140 align:middle line:90%
but it's the ninth volume.

00:07:08.140 --> 00:07:10.400 align:middle line:84%
>> So what happened to
him during these days,

00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:11.800 align:middle line:90%
these three days?

00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:17.110 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, here he is, this
entrepreneur with his very

00:07:17.110 --> 00:07:22.030 align:middle line:84%
materialistic mindset in the
company of a younger, blonde,

00:07:22.030 --> 00:07:27.290 align:middle line:84%
attractive woman who lives
there in the depth of the taiga

00:07:27.290 --> 00:07:29.740 align:middle line:90%
without any modern amenities.

00:07:29.740 --> 00:07:32.560 align:middle line:84%
When he arrived to
her home, he couldn't

00:07:32.560 --> 00:07:37.240 align:middle line:84%
see any kind of man-made shelter
and she was not even allowing

00:07:37.240 --> 00:07:39.640 align:middle line:90%
him to light the fire.

00:07:39.640 --> 00:07:41.660 align:middle line:84%
>> Let's talk about the
word taiga for a moment,

00:07:41.660 --> 00:07:43.630 align:middle line:84%
because I think a lot of people
outside of Russia don't know

00:07:43.630 --> 00:07:44.430 align:middle line:90%
what that means.

00:07:44.430 --> 00:07:46.870 align:middle line:90%
>> Taiga is the northern forest.

00:07:46.870 --> 00:07:49.030 align:middle line:84%
Basically it's a
conifer forest-- fir

00:07:49.030 --> 00:07:53.050 align:middle line:84%
trees and pine trees
and large trees,

00:07:53.050 --> 00:07:57.400 align:middle line:84%
which is predominant
throughout most of the Siberia

00:07:57.400 --> 00:08:00.400 align:middle line:90%
and in parts of northern Canada.

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:02.710 align:middle line:10%
>> So he's now out in
the conifers with her,

00:08:02.710 --> 00:08:07.810 align:middle line:10%
out in the forest at her home
place and he can't see a home

00:08:07.810 --> 00:08:09.320 align:middle line:10%
or anything else
for that matter.

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:10.120 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:08:10.120 --> 00:08:11.950 align:middle line:84%
And she even thinks
that this is where

00:08:11.950 --> 00:08:16.420 align:middle line:84%
she lives and this is where
she had lived all her life.

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:20.020 align:middle line:84%
And he gets a shock
and even wants

00:08:20.020 --> 00:08:21.610 align:middle line:84%
to run back to the
bank of the river

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:25.180 align:middle line:84%
to be picked up
by his steamboat.

00:08:25.180 --> 00:08:35.440 align:middle line:84%
But her-- the sheer abnormality
of the whole situation

00:08:35.440 --> 00:08:38.470 align:middle line:84%
makes him stay because he is
keen to discover this tree

00:08:38.470 --> 00:08:40.000 align:middle line:90%
and to learn more.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.980 align:middle line:84%
And he witnesses the amazing
harmonious interaction

00:08:44.980 --> 00:08:50.830 align:middle line:84%
that Anastasia enjoys with
plants and animals on the way

00:08:50.830 --> 00:08:51.780 align:middle line:90%
that she lives.

00:08:51.780 --> 00:08:53.930 align:middle line:84%
Squirrels bring her
food to eat and she

00:08:53.930 --> 00:08:58.570 align:middle line:84%
is not concerned about providing
for her food or for her shelter

00:08:58.570 --> 00:09:00.550 align:middle line:84%
and sleeps in one of
the dugouts that are

00:09:00.550 --> 00:09:03.510 align:middle line:90%
prepared for her by the bear.

00:09:03.510 --> 00:09:05.330 align:middle line:90%
>> And sometimes with bears.

00:09:05.330 --> 00:09:06.130 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:09:06.130 --> 00:09:08.330 align:middle line:90%
This was his first experience.

00:09:08.330 --> 00:09:12.910 align:middle line:84%
To keep him warm,
she invited him

00:09:12.910 --> 00:09:16.240 align:middle line:84%
to sleep in the same
dugout with the bear

00:09:16.240 --> 00:09:18.850 align:middle line:84%
and he thought it
was just the pelt,

00:09:18.850 --> 00:09:22.690 align:middle line:84%
but it turned out that
it was a living creature.

00:09:22.690 --> 00:09:27.010 align:middle line:84%
And you know, it may
sound too far out.

00:09:27.010 --> 00:09:31.320 align:middle line:84%
But people who are
familiar with this region,

00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:37.060 align:middle line:84%
they will tell you that many
local people can communicate

00:09:37.060 --> 00:09:40.210 align:middle line:84%
with the local
wildlife, with bears,

00:09:40.210 --> 00:09:45.850 align:middle line:84%
and there is no fantastic in
his account up to this point.

00:09:45.850 --> 00:09:49.090 align:middle line:84%
>> And it's true even in even
in the Western world through

00:09:49.090 --> 00:09:53.980 align:middle line:84%
the Disney-type of renditions
of this and movies of Snow White

00:09:53.980 --> 00:09:56.710 align:middle line:84%
and Sleeping Beauty, where
they go into the forest,

00:09:56.710 --> 00:10:00.760 align:middle line:84%
the one common denominator is
that the young woman is always

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:03.670 align:middle line:84%
able to live in harmony with and
communicate with the animals,

00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:07.130 align:middle line:84%
which growing up, I thought that
was the most beautiful thing

00:10:07.130 --> 00:10:07.930 align:middle line:90%
imaginable.

00:10:07.930 --> 00:10:09.910 align:middle line:84%
So it must be some
recognition inside of us

00:10:09.910 --> 00:10:11.590 align:middle line:90%
that is drawn to that.

00:10:11.590 --> 00:10:14.350 align:middle line:10%
Our own human capability
to be able to do this

00:10:14.350 --> 00:10:16.000 align:middle line:10%
has to be innate to us.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:18.970 align:middle line:84%
>> Exactly, because this is
the image of the Paradise Lost.

00:10:18.970 --> 00:10:19.790 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:10:19.790 --> 00:10:23.440 align:middle line:84%
>> And he starts to
discourage her lifestyle,

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:28.360 align:middle line:84%
which is shocking to him,
but she very patiently tried

00:10:28.360 --> 00:10:31.840 align:middle line:84%
to explain to him in the very
simple terms that he would be

00:10:31.840 --> 00:10:37.330 align:middle line:84%
able to relate to how nature
of her lifestyle was and how

00:10:37.330 --> 00:10:43.240 align:middle line:84%
in nature our civilization is
compared to the way she and her

00:10:43.240 --> 00:10:46.930 align:middle line:84%
ancestors had always lived
in this part of Siberia.

00:10:46.930 --> 00:10:48.070 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:10:48.070 --> 00:10:48.460 align:middle line:90%
Go ahead.

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:49.293 align:middle line:90%
I was going to say--

